panding the nation’s and the region’s archives. They enrich our understanding of black Canada by bringing to light the prairies' black histories, cultures, and presences.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAuthors, BlackzCanada. 0aAuthors, BlackzPrairie Provinces. 0aCanadian literaturexBlack authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aCanadian literaturexBlack authors. 0aCanadian literaturezPrairie ProvincesxHistory and criticism. 0aCanadian literaturezPrairie Provinces. 4aArchival Studies. 4aCultural Studies. 4aLiterary Criticism: Canadian Literature. 4aSocial Science: Multiculturalism. 7aLITERARY COLLECTIONS / Canadian.2bisacsh  aBlack Atlantic literature.  aBlack Canadian literature.  aPrairie literature.  aarchives.  ablack history.  aregional literature.  aregionalism.1 aVernon, Karina, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311127363108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2018z978311127598740uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978177112376140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781771123761423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781771123761/original  a978-3-11-127363-1  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-127598-7  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles